\begin_layout Section
MITIGATION
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Mitigation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is unlikely, and perhaps undesirable, that the number of backcountry
 travelers will be reduced.
 Therefore, we must find ways to limit the likelihood of inter-party incidents.
 The following are strategies that may mitigate the risk.
 There are certainly more â€“ these are suggested to organize and catalyze
 discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Awareness and Education
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Awareness of the increasing likelihood of inter-party conflict with density
 may, on its own, help to curtail inter-party involvements.
 That is, of course, the intent of this work.
 In places where the density of travelers approaches the critical density,
 the hazard should be discussed and mitigated.
 At least a passing mention of inter-party hazard in avalanche education
 at all levels now seems prudent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As better understanding of the factors that lead to inter-party avalanche
 involvements becomes understood, it will make sense to bring light to the
 hazard in avalanche bulletins.
 A key takeaway for forecasters is the apparent importance of avalanche
 size in determining the likelihood of inter-party involvements, especially
 in situations (
\emph on
e.g.

\emph default
 persistent weaknesses) where avalanche size alone may not convince travelers
 to stay home.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Density reduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The root of inter-party incidents is not the 
\emph on
number
\emph default
 of backcountry travelers, but their 
\emph on
density
\emph default
.
 Backcountry travelers use a tiny fraction of North American alpine terrain,
 perhaps primarily due to access constraints.
 Following the Kendall Peak accident
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "KendallDecember19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the author has curtailed trips into densely-skied terrain, choosing lesser-kno
wn destinations, difficult access, or lower-quality snow in order to decrease
 overhead risk from other parties.
 While this strategy has limits, lonely places with great skiing still exist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As advocacy organizations work to expand wintertime access, they can add
 safety to the rationale for improved access.
 From our estimates, it is natural to encourage party densities below one
 per characteristic-avalanche-size.
 D2 slides are roughly 0.01 km
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 in area.
 D3 slides are roughly 0.1 km
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 in area
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SWAG"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, encouraging party densities below 10-100 parties/km
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
in localized avalanche terrain
\emph default
 would be wise, and ten-times lower (intimated by Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Approximate-fraction-of"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is prudent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Travel practices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If density cannot be wholly avoided, then we must find ways to limit our
 susceptibility to other parties and the risks we may pose to others.
 We cannot control others' choices, but we can control our own.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Defensive routefinding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like defensive driving, defensive routefinding consists of making choices
 that mitigate the risks that others may pose.
 Careful selection of routes through terrain, and, to a lesser extent, times
 to pass through terrain, can strongly limit the chance that another party's
 avalanche might hit us.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Avalanches only happen in avalanche terrain â€“ avoiding avalanche terrain
 is the sure-fire way to avoid avalanche incidents of all kinds, including
 inter-party incidents.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many ridgelines are not susceptible to slides from above â€“ traveling such
 a route provides substantial protection from inter-party hazard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Some routes pass through areas of unavoidable avalanche hazard â€“ there are
 plenty of examples: The Mousetrap
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MousetrapAsulkanGuide"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 at Rogers Pass, Source Lake Basin and Mushroom Couloir at Snoqualmie Pass.
 Avoiding those areas during times that 
\emph on
human-triggered
\emph default
 slides are likely, rather than only when natural slides are likely, will
 limit the risk of an inter-party incident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Hawkins Mountain (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Hawkins"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and Turbo Hillclimb (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Turbo"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) accidents make clear the danger of extended loitering in inter-party-avalanche
 terrain.
 When assessing safe spots, the likelihood of human triggers above must
 be considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choosing 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 to travel (down or up) routes at times that we expect others might be ascending
 or descending is also a form of defensive routefinding.
 Anticipating the choices of others and making our own conservative diversion
 or delay in order to limit the risks we might present to others is a mark
 of a conscientious traveler.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Active measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we travel in start zones, we are potential triggers for avalanches.
 In addition to passive measures to ensure that we are not traveling above
 other people, there are small measures we can take to communicate with
 those who might be below.
 Radios (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Radios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) are the superior method of communication in the backcountry, but are not
 used by everyone, nor are they completely reliable.
 As a simple measure, rock climbers and mountaineers yell 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Rope!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 before tossing down a rappel rope, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

On Rappel!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 before rappelling (which can dislodge rock), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Off Rappel
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to communicate to those above and below, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Rope
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 again, when the rope is pulled (which can generate more rockfall).
 The wording is important, but in the snow world, something akin to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hello Below!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Skiing!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Clear!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 could provide warning and an opportunity for communication with those below.
 Similarly, for a group entering constrained terrain from below, it might
 be appropriate to shout (or radio (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Radios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

)), 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Entering Couloir!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and make an occasional shout as they ascend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Verbal warnings are, of course, antithetical to a low-impact and quiet winter
 day (and may lead to confusion, as shouts are  a sign of an emergency).
 If the rate of inter-party incidents continues to grow, the necessity of
 such measures, and the approximate skier density at which they are appropriate,
 will become self-evident.
 At a crowded crag, it is perhaps more welcome than it is jarring to hear
 a climber yell, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Rope!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as they begin an orderly descent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to verbal warnings, making micro-route decisions during ascent
 and descent to maximize the leader's ability to see up/down-slope can increase
 the likelihood of noting a potential inter-party conflict before it becomes
 reality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regional travel standards for routes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as we all agree to drive on one side of a road in order to prevent
 head-on automotive collisions, community standards may improve mutually-benefic
ial cooperation between parties who have never met.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Run lists
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In recent years 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NWACRunList,RunListIsraelson"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the notion of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Run List
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has moved from professional operations discussions into the mainstream.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

run list
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a shared enumeration/mapping of regions and ski runs used to facilitate
 discussion and improve adherence to each day's terrain assessment/plan.
 In courses at the Washington Alpine Club, run lists have become an integral
 part of our courses and our students often refer to them after the course
 is complete.
 A publicly-shared run list can serve as a basis for conditions reporting,
 incident response, and general communication.
 While run lists themselves will not offer any advantage for inter-party
 incidents â€“ they may even serve to concentrate travelers during times of
 higher hazard â€“ a strong basis for communication is bedrock upon which
 many mitigation strategies can be built.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Terrain-specific traditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In certain high-density traffic locations, it may be helpful to establish
 certain local traffic patterns.
 The aviation industry has 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Approach Procedures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Instrument Approach Procedures
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (IAP)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "FAAApproaches"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for most airports that describe the airport-specific information needed
 to land and take off safely.
 While IAPs contain a level of detail not needed for backcountry travel,
 the occasional publicized traffic pattern may be of use.
 These may be best described by examples:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Near the Mount Baker Ski Area, there is a backcountry ski run known as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Blueberry Chutes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 It is a high-traffic run in avalanche terrain, 1.5
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

km from a parking lot, with a straightforward and comparatively safe alternative
 ascent route that reaches the run at the top.
 It is also possible to ascend the run directly, which is arduous, slow,
 exposed to avalanche hazard, and exposed to skiers dropping in from above.
